        'desc_en'    => 'Affectionately called by Lacedonian residents simply "Chiesa Madre" or "Cattedrale," the Church of Santa Maria Assunta stands at the heart of the town as the community\'s principal place of worship. Its origins date to the 16th century: where the bell tower now stands, there once stood a modest chapel dedicated to Sant\'Antonio — a place sadly marked by a dramatic historical episode. On the night of 10–11 September 1486, southern nobles in revolt against King Ferrante of Aragon swore here to expel the Aragonese from the Kingdom of Naples. The present church was built in the 16th century and expanded over the following two centuries: the nave was widened from one to three aisles, and the impressive bell tower was erected, which still dominates Lacedonia\'s historic skyline. These works gave the building the grandeur and solemnity typical of Southern Italian Baroque ecclesiastical architecture. The interior preserves frescoes, sacred artworks and furnishings of considerable quality, severely damaged by the 1980 earthquake and subsequently restored. The church has been digitized into a navigable 3D model allowing visitors to admire the details of frescoes and sacred furnishings up close.',
