        'desc_en'    => 'The Chapel of the Holy Trinity is one of Lacedonia\'s oldest and most historically significant places of worship. Its historical importance is attested by an exceptional discovery: local priest and researcher Pasquale Palmese found inside the chapel a Latin inscription belonging to Lucius Licinius, descendant of Marcus Licinius Mager, a member of the Roman Galeria tribe — concrete proof of the existence of a Roman settlement in the Lacedonian territory. The current building is not the original: the numerous earthquakes that have struck the area destroyed the primitive church. In 1600 Bishop La Morea ordered its complete reconstruction. On the stone entrance doorway, two slabs bear Latin inscriptions: "SANCTA TRINITAS VNVS DEVS MISERERE NOBIS" and an inscription referencing the bishop who oversaw the works. Damaged again by the earthquake of 23 November 1980, the chapel was reopened to the faithful only in July 2002. A further layer of spirituality is added by the connection to San Gerardo Maiella, who according to tradition expelled the devil from this place after having been forced to follow him to Lacedonia on a stormy night. Since 2010, a large ceramic painting on the external wall commemorates this event. The Feast of the Holy Trinity, held in the first decade of June, enlivens the community with traditional games and moments of togetherness.',
