        'desc_en'    => 'A short distance from Lacedonia\'s historic centre lies one of eastern Irpinia\'s most precious natural corners: Capi dell\'Acqua, a natural spring of rare beauty immersed in lush vegetation. The name itself — "Capi dell\'Acqua" (Headwaters) — reflects the numerous freshwater springs that emerge from the limestone rocks, forming crystal-clear streams that flow through ancient oak and chestnut forests. The area is an ecosystem of exceptional biodiversity: numerous species of birds and amphibians find their natural habitat here, making the site a favoured destination for birdwatching and nature observation. The paths that wind between the springs allow hikes accessible to families, immersed in the pristine nature of the Campano-Lucanian Apennines. The significance of Capi dell\'Acqua is not only naturalistic: from prehistory — when the tuff caves of the territory were already inhabited over 13,000 years ago — through the Roman period and the episodes of post-unification brigandage, these springs have represented a vital resource for local populations. Today they could become the focal point of a slow and sustainable tourism offer, with guided trails, environmental education activities and a model of valorisation that brings together history, nature and community. The MetaBorghi virtual tour documents the area in an immersive 360° experience.',
